::: callout-warning
## The ten percent rule

The ten percent rule is a common technique in epidemiology and other fields to determine whether a variable is a confounder.
The ten percent rule says that you should include a variable in your model if including it changes the effect estimate by more than ten percent.
The problem is, it doesn't work.
*Every* example in the causal quartet causes a change of more than ten percent.
As we know, this leads to the wrong answer in some of the datasets.
Even the reverse technique, *disincluding* a variable when it's *less* than ten percent, can cause trouble because many small confounding effects can add up to larger bias.


::: {#tbl-quartet_ten_percent .cell tbl-cap='The percent change in the coefficient for `exposure` when including `covariate` in the model.'}
::: {.cell-output-display}

